Prediction of Intraday Stock Market Prices of F.A.A.N.G. Companies using Sentiment Scores in GDELT Global Knowledge Graph V2.1¶

Executive Summary¶

New advancement in technology gave birth to the Algorithmic Trading paradigm. Traders, programmers, and researchers alike are taking advantage of Big Data from both digital and non digital channels and transform them into valauble information that complement traditional trading indicators (e.g. moving average, RSI, etc.). Furthermore, Machine Learning has allowed a purely data-driven approach in predicting stock price movements; that is, without the use of domain knowledge or theoretical trading models.

One key task in the field is the translation of news (or event) sentiments as market indicators that boosts the prediction accuracies. Traditional approaches to the task include the extraction of sentiment scores from social media chatter and news articles. While these approaches prove useful, they involve a lot of steps and the use of multiple APIs. This is further complicated by defining query terms that may or may not be comprehensive for the analysis.

The limitations in traditional approaches led us to consider the Global Knowledge Graph (GKG) database, a global compilation of documents available in almost 100 languages. Each document in the GKG database has a tagged entity and a computed sentiment score. Utilizing the GKG allows us to focus on defining search queries without worrying about the APIs, webscraping, and preprocessing.

For this paper, we present a methodology that allows us to incorporate sentiment scores from the GKG database in the prediction of stock price movement of FAANG companies (Facebook, Amazon, Apple, Netflix, and Google). We processed GKG records from May 2017 to December 2017 using PySpark and extracted entries relevant to the companies of interest. We also filtered out non-Finance news and mean-aggregated the sentiment scores by the hour. Meanwhile, hourly stock price movement for FAANG companies were obtained from Kaggle.

We were able to produce satisfying results using a Gradient Boosted Tree Regressor, sentiment scores from GKG, and other features extracted from the time series. We recommend that future studies may explore the use of other machine learning models (regressors and classifiers), and the use of deep learning models such as LSTM and Bi-LSTM in predicting stock price movements. Further, we recommend to extend the time span from 6 months to several years to see how much effective GKG can be in complementing existing approaches to Algorithmic Trading

Introduction¶

New York is home to the two largest securities exchange in the world in terms of market capitalization: the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) and the Nasdaq Stock Market (NASDAQ). (Corporate Finance Institute, n.d.; World Federation of Exchanges, 2014; Investopedia, 2020) While NYSE has the larger market capitalization (U SD 22.38 Trillion) (TradingHours.com), NASDAQ (Market Capitalization: USD 16.10 Trillion) (TradingHours.com) houses most technology-first growth companies like Apple, Facebook, Google, Microsoft, Netflix, Amazon, and the like.

Trading in the stock market has always been a topic for discussion, especially not that the world's largest markets are recovering from the dip in early 2020. Among market players, traders and investors are differentiated by their investing horizon and perspective on returns. Traders experience higher returns from trades dictated by observed price movements. Meanwhile, investors ignore short-term volatility and focus on the long-term growth potential of the stock. While both rely on fundamentals and technical indicators, it can be observed that traders rely more on technical indicators than investors.

Advancements in technology have resulted into a shift to Algorithmic Trading paradigms which have become more popular due Big Data and machine learning algorithms. Algorithmic trading involves pre-programmed trading instructions that account for time, volume, price, and other potential market indicators to predict price movements in and "win a market" (Kharysh, 2019). Over the years, traders and developers alike have developed long short-term memory neural networks and reinforcement learning models to improve prediction accuracies and account for inherent fuzziness and volatility of the market.

One specific task that caught the attention of many researchers is the incorporation of relevant and real-time market sentiments from multimedia, not limited to news articles and social media chatter. Multimedia sources may be a combination of social media activity, reactions to news articles, release of positive or negative publicity materials, general mood on economy, and the like. (Kharysh, 2019).

Stock Price Growth of Technology Companies¶

The 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic has forced the world to speed up their digital transformation initiatives making 2020 a defining moment for the technology sector. In an interview, Microsoft (MSFT) CEO Satya Nadella even commented that "[We've seen] two year's worth of digital transformation [happen] in two months." Technology adoption increase and business landscape changes brought by the "New Normal" may signal potential growths in the technology sector especially since customer behavior and market sentiment has changed over the past months of community lockdown i.e. work-from-home, e-commerce and online shopping, and virtual events, among others. (Divine, 2020). Among the companies traded in NASDAQ, visible gainers from the pandemic include Amazon (AMZN), Zoom (ZM), Chegg (CHGG) and Teledoc (TDOC), among others (Divine, 2020).

For many investors, brokers, and traders, the rainbow after the rain can be found in these technology companies, or simply, tech stocks. Aside from trading at a modest premium (Divine, 2020), tech stocks have also proven their mettle and resilience from black swans like the pandemic; making them the more attractive option than "Old Normal" stocks such as airline, leisure, and real estate stocks.

Motivation¶

For the reasons mentioned in the previous sections, we decided to look at stock prices of the five prominent American technology companies: Facebook (FB), Amazon (AMZN), Apple (AAPL), Netflix (NFLX), and Alphabet (GOOGL) or F.A.A.N.G. (FAANG) and validate the advantage of using market multimedia sentiments in the Global Database of Events, Tone, and Languages (GDELT) in Algorithmic Trading. We extracted hourly contents related to each FAANG company from May to December 2017 and used sentiment measures (under V1.5TONE) as features to predict hourly intra-day prices using a simple machine learning model.

Business Value¶

With this project, we aim to help investors develop a methodology using real-time world news sentiment (Big Data) that can complement existing methodologies or algorithms.

Dataset¶

News Sentiments from Global Knowledge Graph gkg¶

The GDELT project is a global database of society. It monitors the world's broadcast, print and web news from nearly every country in the world in mode than 100 languages. One of these databases is the Global Knowledge Graph (GKG). It compiles a list of several million themes and thousands of emotions from every news report. In total, GKG V2.1 contains 5.7 Terabytes of data colleted since 2015. It has 27 features containing meta information for every multimedia available in the globe.

Out of the 27, the features of interest for the study are V21DATE, V2SOURCECOLLECTIONIDENTIFIER, V2SOURCECOMMONNAME, V2DOCUMENTIDENTIFIER, V1ORGANIZATION, V15TONE, V2GCAM, and V2ALLNAMES. For a complete discussion of the GKG dataset and its contents, you may visit the official documentation here. We describe below the relevant features for the study.

Variable Data Type Description
V2.1DATE INT Datetime in format YYYMMDDHHMMSS
V2SOURCECOLLECTIONIDENTIFIER INT Numeric identifier of the document source. 1: WEB, 2: CITATIONONLY, 3: CORE, 4: DTIC, 5: JSTOR, 6: NONTEXTUAL SOURCE
V2SOURCECOMMONNAME STR Name of the document source origin
V2DOCUMENTIDENTIFIER STR Direct Link to the source document
V1ORGANIZATION SDV list of companies and organization names found in the text
V1.5TONE CSV Comma-delimited list of six core emotional dimensions: TONE, POSITIVE_SCORE, NEGATIVE_SCORE, POLARITY, ACTIVITY_DENSITY, SELF_REFERENCE_DENSITY, and WORD_COUNT
V2GCAM CSV Topic Identifier based on the Global Context Analysis Measures (GCAM). More information here. Details will be shared on the Methodology Section.
V2ALLNAMES STR List of all proper names referenced in the document

*SDV - Semicolon Delimited Values

The GKG dataset can be accessed in this S3 bucket.

For the project, we extracted items/ rows that mentioned the FAANG companies and its associates in the V1ORGANIZATION and V2ALLNAMES columns. We also extracted each emotional dimension in V15TONE to separate columns. The time frame is matched with available stock price in the Kaggle dataset we found here

Intra-day Stock Price Movements stock¶

Stocks prices for Facebook, Amazon, Apple, Netflix and Google (FAANG) were downloaded from the Kaggle dataset "Daily and Intraday Stock Price Data". Available here. The dataset contains stock price the target companies available in time periods of 5 minutes, 1 hour and 1 day. Since the GKG dataset is aggregated every 15 minutes, we decided to take the 1 hour stock price movements and match it with the average sentiment scores during the hour. The following table describes the content of the Stock dataset

Variable Type Description
Date Datetime Date of Trade in yyyy-mm-dd
Time Time Time of Trade in hh:mm:ss
Open Float Opening Price for the time period
Low Float Lowest Price for the time period
High Float Highest Price for the time period
Close Float Closing Price for the time period
Volume Float Trade Volume for the time period

The dataset contains data from 16 May 2017 to 06 December 2017. A copy of the relevant tech stocks were uploaded in a private S3 bucket for ease of access by the Spark Cluster.

Methodology¶

General Workflow¶

The set-up for the paper is as follow:

  1. Data Extraction and Cleaning

    • Processing of the gkg dataset from the s3://gdelt-open-data/v2/gkg and extract relevant entries per FAANG company and averaging of sentiment measures per hour.
    • Extraction of hourly closing tech stock price from stock
    • Matching of stock and gkg entries using JOIN methods
    • Handling of Missing Values

  2. Exploratory Data Analysis

    • Data Description and Return distribution of relevant tech stocks
    • Autocorrelation Plots of Stock Prices
    • Description of Sentiment Scores and Feature Correlations

  3. Implementation of Machine Learning Models

    • Data Preprocessing/ Set-up
    • Machine Learning Implementation

Spark Cluster Setup¶

An Elastic Map Reduce (Spark) Cluster composed of 1 Master Node (m4.large) and 5 Core Nodes (m4.large) was created. Basic Python libraries like pandas, matplotlib, and numpy were installed using the Command Line Interface.

Data Extraction and Cleaning¶

Extraction of FAANG Stocks stock¶

Each FAANG Stock (*.us.txt) is stored in a variable as a Spark Dataframe. Only the Date, Time, and Close columns were used. The return of a stock $R_t$ at time $t$ is computed as,

\begin{align*} R_t &= \frac{S_t - S_{t-1}}{S_{t-1}} \end{align*}

where $S_t$ is the stock price at time $t$.

This can also be interpreted as the the percentage change in the stock price.

A lookback of 1 time step was also generated for Close and Return columns; these values are stored in prevClose and prevReturn, respectively. Date and Time are merged as the timestamp column, dateTime. Below shows the implementation and the schema of the resulting Spark DataFrames. We will be using the Stock Price Return as the target variable as it is stationary. Null values are dropped at the final merge of the stock and gkg dataframes.

def get_stock_data(stock_code='fb', start='2017-05-01 00:00:00', 
                   end='2017-12-31 23:59:59'):
    """Returns the Stock returns of the stocks `sdf` from `start` to `end`."""
    
    sdf = spark.read.csv(f's3://dump-bdcc-2021/{stock_code}.us.txt', 
                         header=True)
    my_window = Window.partitionBy().orderBy('Date')
    sdf = (sdf.select(col('Date').cast('date'), 
                col('Time'),
                col('Close').cast('float'))
         .withColumn('dateTime', 
                     to_timestamp(F.concat(col('Date'), F.lit(' '), 
                                           col('Time')), 
                                  'yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss'))
         .withColumn('prevClose', 
                     F.lag('Close', 1).over(my_window).cast('float'))
         .withColumn('Return', 
                     (col('Close')-col('prevClose'))/col('prevClose'))
         .withColumn('prevReturn', 
                     F.lag(col('Return'), 1).over(my_window).cast('float'))
         .drop('Date', 'Time')
         .filter(col('dateTime').between(start, end))
           )
    print(f'Extracted {sdf.distinct().count()} '
          f'stock entries for ${stock_code.upper()}.')
    return sdf

Extraction of relevant gkg entries from S3¶

Each gkg file in the S3 bucket follows the same file name convention /YYYYMMDDHHMMSS*.gkg.csv. We obtained all csv files from May 2017 to December 2017 that falls under the trading hours specified in the stock dateTime column. After filtering the entries, we extracted the sentiment scores from the V15TONE column and stored them in their respective columns TONE, POSITIVE_SCORE, NEGATIVE_SCORE, POLARITY, ACTIVITY_DENSITY, SELF_REFERENCES, and WORD_COUNT. We also create DATE and HOUR columns that extracts date and hour data from V21DATE.

There are a total of 19,511,607 rows in the gkg Spark DataFrame.

split_col = split(gkg['V15TONE'], ',')
gkg = (gkg.withColumn('TONE', split_col.getItem(0).cast('float'))
          .withColumn('POSITIVE_SCORE', split_col.getItem(1).cast('float'))
          .withColumn('NEGATIVE_SCORE', split_col.getItem(2).cast('float'))
          .withColumn('POLARITY', split_col.getItem(3).cast('float'))
          .withColumn('ACTIVITY_DENSITY', split_col.getItem(4).cast('float'))
          .withColumn('SELF_REFERENCES', split_col.getItem(5).cast('float'))
          .withColumn('WORD_COUNT', split_col.getItem(6).cast('float'))
          .withColumn('V21DATE', to_timestamp(gkg.V21DATE, 'yyyyMMddHHmmss'))
          .withColumn('DATE', col('V21DATE').cast('date'))
          .withColumn('HOUR', hour(col('V21DATE')))
          .drop('V15TONE')
      )

Filtering of Relevant FAANG related Financial and Economic Entries from gkg

In order to filter entries related to the FAANG companies, we took advantage of the V21ALLNAMES and the V1ORGANIZATIONS column of gkg. These column contain all mentioned proper nouns/ names and organizations in the specific entry. We identied several terminologies that we believe are associated with the FAANG company. Most of these terms are affiliate organizations and acquisitions of said companies. We refrained from including products and services to enhance focus on the traded company itself. Below shows the list of words we used as queries

Company Affiliates (Terms to look for)
Facebook 'facebook', 'whatsapp', 'instagram', 'giphy', 'oculus', 'workplace by facebook', 'facebook reality labs', 'facebook blockchain'
Apple 'apple', 'shazam', 'siri', 'emagic', 'beats electronics', 'next inc', 'novauris', 'primesense', 'apple pay'
Amazon 'amazon', 'imdb', 'alexa.com', 'audible', 'zappos', 'annapurna labs', 'goodreads', 'twitch', 'kiva systems', 'amazon robotics', 'whole foods market'
Netflix 'netflix', 'millarworld'
Google/ Alphabet 'google', 'alphabet', 'adsense', 'doubleclick', 'youtube', 'google maps', 'gmail', 'google drive'

We also acknowledge that entries may not be about the company's performance in the stock market. We utilized the Global Content Analysis Measures (GCAM) to avoid entries that are not related to financial or economic performance of the traded company. According to the GDELT website, "The GCAM system runs each news article monitored by GDELT through an array of leading content analysis tools to capture over 2,230 latent dimensions, reporting density and valye scores for each." GCAM allows us to identify and filter topics from the gkg corpus; enhancing the focus of the selected documents.

GCAM also provides a codebook here that contains all positive topic tag. From the codebook, we identified the following tags as relevant for the project.

Topic Tag GCAM Description

c18.54 ECON_BANKRUPTCY
c18.59 ECON_STOCKMARKET
c18.60 ECON_EARNINGSREPORT

def get_faang(fp='s3://dump-bdcc-2021/faang_v3.csv'):
    """Load the faang dataset from S3"""
    
    from pyspark.sql.types import (TimestampType, DecimalType, 
                                   IntegerType, DateType, StringType)
    header = ['V21DATE', 'V2SOURCECOLLECTIONIDENTIFIER', 'V2SOURCECOMMONNAME', 
         'V2DOCUMENTIDENTIFIER', 'V1ORGANIZATIONS', 'V21ALLNAMES', 'TONE', 
         'POSITIVE_SCORE', 'NEGATIVE_SCORE', 'POLARITY', 'ACTIVITY_DENSITY',
         'SELF_REFERENCES', 'WORD_COUNT', 'DATE', 'HOUR']
    dtypes = [TimestampType, IntegerType, StringType, 
              StringType, StringType, StringType,
             DecimalType, DecimalType, DecimalType,
             DecimalType, DecimalType, DecimalType, 
              IntegerType, DateType, IntegerType]
    faang = spark.read.csv(fp).toDF(*header)
    for header, dtype in zip(header, dtypes):
        faang = faang.withColumn(header, F.col(header).cast(dtype()))
        
    return faang

faang = get_faang('s3://dump-bdcc-2021/faang_v3.csv').persist()

def get_company_from_faang(faang, company, stock_code):
    """Extract company specific entries from `faang` with Sentiment 
    Scores averaged by the hour."""
    
    sdf = (faang.filter(faang['V1ORGANIZATIONS'].rlike('|'.join(company)) |
                         faang['V21ALLNAMES'].rlike('|'.join(company)))
                 .groupby('DATE', 'HOUR')
                 .avg('TONE', 'POSITIVE_SCORE', 
                      'NEGATIVE_SCORE', 'POLARITY', 
                      'ACTIVITY_DENSITY', 'SELF_REFERENCES', 
                      'WORD_COUNT')
                 .orderBy('DATE', 'HOUR')
                 .withColumn('dateTime', to_timestamp(F.concat(col('DATE'), 
                                                           F.lit(' '), 
                                                           col('HOUR'), 
                                                           F.lit(':00:00')),
                                                      'yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss'))
                 .drop('DATE', 'HOUR')
          )
    
    print(f'Extracted {sdf.distinct().count()} news '
          f'entries for ${stock_code.upper()}.')

    return sdf

Joining with stock dataset

In the following cell, we conduct a LEFT JOIN (stock and sdf) and retain the dateTime column of stock. This matches sentiment scores from the previous section to each stock price in the stock dataset. We removed NaN values associated with prevClose and prevReturn. Missing values in the sentiment columns are handled using forward filling followed by backward filling. This assumes that sentiments remained constant until the next "big" thing comes along.

In [43]:
def join_stock_gkg(stock, sdf, impute=True):
    """Join `sdf` with `stock` using LEFT JOIN 
    (retaining the dataTime of `stock`)"""
    
    res = (stock.alias('a').join(sdf.alias('b'), 
                                 stock['dateTime']==sdf['dateTime'], 'left')
                .drop('avg(WORD_COUNT)')
                .select('a.Return', 'a.prevReturn', 
                        'a.Close', 'a.prevClose', 'b.*')
                .orderBy('dateTime'))
    
    if impute:
        import sys
        float_cols = ['avg(TONE)','avg(NEGATIVE_SCORE)', 
                      'avg(POSITIVE_SCORE)', 'avg(POLARITY)', 
                      'avg(ACTIVITY_DENSITY)', 'avg(SELF_REFERENCES)']
        clean_cols = ['TONE', 'NEGATIVE_SCORE', 'POSITIVE_SCORE', 
                      'POLARITY', 'ACTIVITY_DENSITY', 'SELF_REFERENCES']
        
        window_f = Window.rowsBetween(-sys.maxsize, 0)
        window_b = Window.rowsBetween(0, sys.maxsize,)
        for float_col, clean_col in zip(float_cols, clean_cols):

            res = (res.withColumn(clean_col,  
                                  F.last(res[float_col], 
                                         ignorenulls=True).over(window_f))
                     .withColumn(clean_col, 
                                 F.first(col(clean_col), 
                                         ignorenulls=True).over(window_b)))
            
            
        res = res.drop(*float_cols)
        
    return res.na.drop()

Autocorrelations of Closing Stock Price¶

The stock price plots in Figure 1 shows observable seasonality, noise, and trends. These artefacts make the trends not stationary and difficult to model. In order to make our data stationary, we subtracted a lag of the time series to itself and use that as a target variable -- the stock return column! The differenced series does not exhibit any seasonality and autocorrelations.

We use the time differenced version to allow the model to learn the true variations/ noise in the series. We can correct for the time lag by doing the inverse of the differencing function.

Recall that the Stock Return Return is given by:

\begin{align*} R_t &= \frac{S_t - S_{t-1}}{S_{t-1}} \end{align*}

We can compute for the Closing Price by computing for $S_t$

\begin{align*} S_t &= (R_t+1)\;S_{t-1} \end{align*}

The next set of visuals shows us the Autocorrelation plots per each Stock Price side-by-side with its Stock Return (differenced series).

def plot_correlation(df, label='stock', ax=None):
    """Plot correlation heat map of `df` using `ax`"""
    features = df.columns.drop('dateTime').tolist()
    corr = df.drop(['dateTime'], axis=1).corr().round(2)
    if ax == None:

    ax.set_title(f'Feature Correlation Values for {label}')

    ax.set_yticks(range(0, len(features)))
    ax.set_xticklabels(features, rotation=90)
    ax.set_yticklabels(features, rotation=0)
    
    return ax

Prediction of Stock Returns (and Closing Price) using GBTRegression Model¶

For the prediction, we implemented a Gradient Boosted Tree Regression (pyspark.ml.regression.GBTRegression) on the selected features from the Exploratory Data Analysis: TONE, POLARITY', ACTIVITY_DENSITY, prevClose, SELF_REFERENCES, and prevReturn. We used the stock Return as the target variable. We decided to include prevReturn as a feature because our analysis show that it is not correlated to the target variable.

Defining Train-Test Split

We define an 80-20 train-test split for the implementation. To be consistent, we spliced the time series at 31 October 2017 and used series data from 1 November 2017 to 6 December 2017 as test data. We stored the train and test sets in a dictionary to improve code readability and to make data calls faster, simpler, and more intuitive.

In [176]:
def split_train_test(sdf, 
                     test_split='2017-10-31 23:59:59',
                     start='2017-05-01 00:00:00', 
                     end='2017-12-31 23:59:59', 
                     stock_code='stock'):
    """Slice the time series based on `test_split`. 
    Returns train and test split of `sdf`."""

    train = sdf.filter(col('dateTime').between(start, test_split))
    test = sdf.filter(col('dateTime').between(test_split, end))
    print(f'Size of (Train, Test) Sets for ${stock_code.upper()}: ', 
                 (train.distinct().count(), 
                  test.distinct().count()))
    
    return train, test

Model Training and Evaluation

We chose a Gradient Boosted Tree (GBT) Regression as the model to combine the benefits of ensemble training (use of multiple trees/ estimators), and the power of gradient boosting in improving the performance of weak learners. We set maxDepth = 5 since GBTs easily overfit at high depth.

In [204]:
from pyspark.ml.evaluation import RegressionEvaluator
from pyspark.ml import Pipeline
from pyspark.ml.regression import GBTRegressor
from pyspark.ml.feature import VectorAssembler
from pyspark.ml.feature import StandardScaler

def compute_predictClose(sdf):
    """Compute the predicted `Close` price based on 
    predicted Returns as a new column in the `sdf`"""
    return (sdf.orderBy('dateTime')
              .withColumn('predictClose', 
                          col('prevClose') * (1+ col('prediction'))))
              
    
def train_model(train, test, Model=None, target='Return', 
                Scaler=StandardScaler, stock_label='Stock' ):
    """Trains a regressor `Model` (default GBTRegressor) with `target` as
    y values. Returns the `train` and `test` spark DataFrames with
    a prediction column."""

    feature_columns = ['TONE', 'POLARITY', 'ACTIVITY_DENSITY', 
                       'prevClose', 'SELF_REFERENCES', 'prevReturn']
    if Model == None:
        Model = GBTRegressor(featuresCol='features_scaled', 
                         labelCol=target, 
                         maxDepth=5, 
                         maxIter=100)

    pipe = Pipeline(stages=[
        VectorAssembler(inputCols=feature_columns, outputCol='features'), 
        Scaler(inputCol='features', outputCol='features_scaled'),
        Model
            ])

    model_trained = pipe.fit(train)
    test_predict = model_trained.transform(test)
    train_predict = model_trained.transform(train)

    evaluator = RegressionEvaluator(labelCol=target)
    print(f'Evaluating trained model results for {stock_label}:')
    print('\tTrain mse: ', evaluator.evaluate(train_predict, 
                                            {evaluator.metricName: 'mse'}))
    print('\tTest mse: ', evaluator.evaluate(test_predict, 
                                           {evaluator.metricName: 'mse'}))
    
    return (compute_predictClose(train_predict), 
            compute_predictClose(test_predict),
            pipe)

Use of Mean Squared Error as Loss Function

Since the mean of Stock Returns is zero we can expect that it can be naively approximated by a horizontal line. That said, using $R^2$ as an accuracy measure will yield negative values, if not zero values. To account for estimation errors, we decided to use Mean Squared Error. The metric penalizes huge errors than small errors allowing us the model to learn spikes in the Return plot.

%%local 

def plot_results(train, test, stock_label='stock'):
    """Plot results given a stock train and test dataframes"""
    
    def generate_figure():
        """Return axes for plotting"""
        fig = plt.figure(constrained_layout=True, figsize=(3.5*2, 3.5*3))
        gs = fig.add_gridspec(3, 2)
        ax = fig.add_subplot(gs[0, :])
        (bx1, bx2) = fig.add_subplot(gs[1, 0]), fig.add_subplot(gs[1, 1])
        (cx1, cx2) = fig.add_subplot(gs[2, 0]), fig.add_subplot(gs[2, 1])
        return fig, [ax, bx1, bx2, cx1, cx2]

    fig, axes = generate_figure()
    start = 0
    train_end = len(train)
    end = train_end + len(test)
    time_range = (train.dateTime.dt.date.tolist()+
                  test.dateTime.dt.date.tolist())
    
    # Plot Full Time Range
    new_axes = []
    axes[0].plot(train.dateTime.dt.date, train.Close, 
                 color='gray', label='actual')
    axes[0].plot(test.dateTime.dt.date, test.Close, color='black')
    axes[0].plot(test.dateTime.dt.date, test.predictClose, '--y')
    axes[0].set_title(f'Prediction Comparison for {stock_label}')
    axes[0].set_ylabel('Share price (USD/ share)')
    axes[0].set_xlabel('Time')
    axes[0].legend(loc='upper left')
    
    new_axes.append(axes[0])
    for bx, actual, predict, label in zip(axes[1:3],
                                          [train.Close, test.Close], 
                                          [train.predictClose,
                                          test.predictClose], 
                                          ['train', 'test']):
        bx.plot(actual, color='black', label='actual')
        bx.plot(predict, '--y', label='predict')
        bx.set_title(f'{label.title()} set results (Close Price)')
        bx.set_ylabel('Share price (USD/ share)')
        bx.set_xlabel('Timestep')
        bx.legend(loc='upper left')
        new_axes.append(bx)
        
        
    for cx, actual, predict, label in zip(axes[3:5],
                                          [train.Return, test.Return], 
                                          [train.prediction,
                                          test.prediction], 
                                          ['train', 'test']):
        cx.plot(actual, color='black', label='actual')
        cx.plot(predict, '--y', label='predict')
        cx.set_title(f'{label.title()} set results (Stock Returns)')
        cx.set_ylabel('Stock Return')
        cx.set_xlabel('Timestep')
        cx.legend(loc='upper left')
        new_axes.append(cx)
        
    return new_axes

General Observations¶

Overall, all predictions was able to capture the behavior of the stock with minimal (and forgivable) over estimations. Surprisingly, the model was able to fit the training set well -- a sign of overfitting. Gradient Boosted Trees loves to overfit to the training data in hopes of generalizing well in the test set.

Some models were able to capture (and predict) spikes and trends in the Stock Return test set and that shows how well the estimator is. However, it can also be argued that the results of the model is an artefact of the use of intraday price movements, which are more granullar (and easier to trace) than daily price movements.

We decided to not conduct a hyper parameter tuning step because we are satisfied with the MSE computed by the Regression Evaluator. Furthermore, it was able to provide a satisfying test set prediction results.

Prediction Results for FB

For Facebook, the model was not able to capture two major dips in the Return Test set -- it predicted it several time steps in advance. However, translating it to Closing prices, it seems to approximate the trend well, sans the two dips mentioned earlier. In hindsight, the preempted dips could have served as a warning from any trader that a huge drop will happen in the future.

Interetingly for Netflix it was able to identify and follow almost all spikes/ peaks in the Test set stock returns with slight variances. This is shown clearly in the test Closing Prices as it gives a good approximation.

Results for GOOGL is looks promising from a Close Price perspective. While it did not identify all peaks and spikes in the Test Stock returns, the overall direction of "spikes" was predicted i.e. there were no opposite/ behavior observed that may cause a huge deviation from actual values.

Conclusions and Recommendations¶

In this paper, we managed to demostrate how the sentiments scores in the Global Knowledge Graph (GKG) can be used as stock market price indicators with features extracted from the time series with satisfying results. However, we also observed that models were not able to accurately predict the test set and were only able to model price direction. As such, we recommend the use of other machine learning models (regressors and classifiers), and the use of deep learning models such as LSTM and Bi-LSTM to enhance the results. Further, we recommend to use daily price stock movements over a larger time span (preferably, 2 years) to assess the viability of the methodology since we hypothesize that granularity of available data (per hour) may have made it easier for the model to trace the path and predict the future values.
